of research and teaching continued in subsequent decades, and recent additions, including critical race studies, queer studies, cultural studies, and postcolonial studies, take as their epistemological foundation the inherently political nature of all knowledge production. Interdisciplinarity and Social Justice seizes this opportune moment in the history of interdisciplinary fields to review their effects on our intellectual and political landscape, to evaluate their ability to deliver promised social benefits, and to consider their futures. The essays collected in this volume detail histories of the interdisciplinary fields that emerged from social movements, examine how effectively they have achieved their goals of intellectual and social change, and consider the challenges they now face inside and outside the academy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInterdisciplinary approach in education. 0aSocial justice. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aEducation : Higher Education. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aSociology : Social Change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBarrett, Lindon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrantlinger, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakravorty, Mrinalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeChaine, D. Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Miranda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuhasz, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowe, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMesser-Davidow, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g